Introduction

As we learned, multinomial model is a type of GLM, so the overall goodness-of-fit statistics and their interpretations and limitations from the first and section of the course still apply.

In SAS, we can easily fitted using PROC LOGISTIC with the link=GLOGIT. We can also use PROC CATMOD and GENMOD. You can use the link to the psu slides to learn about the deatiled usage.

In R there are various packages and function for fitting this model. For example, vglm() from VGAM package, ormultinom() from nnet package, or mlogit() from globaltest package from BIOCONDUCTOR. We will focus on using vglm() in this lab illustration.

Baseline-Category Logit Model

Get data

We will use the alligator data as discussed in class. Researchersclassified the stomach contents of 219 captured alligators into five categories: Fish (the most common primary food choice), Invertebrate (snails, insects, crayfish, etc.), Reptile (turtles, alligators), Bird, and Other (amphibians, plants, household pets, stones, and other debris). In addition to size and lake, the covariates also contain gender of the alligators.

gator <- read.table(file = "gator.txt", header = TRUE)
head(gator)
##   profile Gender Size    Lake Fish Invertebrate Reptile Bird Other
## 1       1      f <2.3  george    3            9       1    0     1
## 2       2      m <2.3  george   13           10       0    2     2
## 3       3      f >2.3  george    8            1       0    0     1
## 4       4      m >2.3  george    9            0       0    1     2
## 5       5      f <2.3 hancock   16            3       2    2     3
## 6       6      m <2.3 hancock    7            1       0    0     5
dim(gator)
## [1] 16  9
gator <- as.data.frame(gator)

Note that the data has already been input as a summary table, which is more convenient for the analysis in R. However, in SAS, it may be better to input the table as single observations like:

Specifying baseline-category logit model

Because the usual primary food choice of alligators appears to be fish, we still use fish as the reference level, as we discussed in class.

### if you haven't install VGAM
# install.packages("VGAM")
library(VGAM)
## Loading required package: stats4
## Loading required package: splines
gator$Lake <- factor(gator$Lake, levels = unique(gator$Lake))
levels(gator$Lake)
## [1] "george"   "hancock"  "oklawaha" "trafford"
contrasts(gator$Lake)=contr.treatment(levels(gator$Lake),base=1)

contrasts(gator$Lake)
##          hancock oklawaha trafford
## george         0        0        0
## hancock        1        0        0
## oklawaha       0        1        0
## trafford       0        0        1

To set up *$“fish” as the baseline**, this can be done in the vglm() call. By default vglm() will use the last category to create the logits. Let see how this is done if we want to fit a model with Lake, Size and Gender as predictors and ‘Fish’ as the baseline for logits:

fit1=vglm(cbind(Bird,Invertebrate,Reptile,Other,Fish)~Lake+Size+Gender, data=gator, family=multinomial)

df = df.residual(fit1)
1 - pchisq(g2, df)
## [1] 0.128185
# pearson test for lack of fit
e = residuals(fit1, type='pearson')
x2 = sum(e^2)
1 - pchisq(x2, df)
## [1] 0.08809151

Cumulative Logit Model

Let’s model with linear effect of dose (scores x = 1, 2, 3, 4) on cumulative logits for outcome.

trauma <- read.table("trauma.txt", header=TRUE)
head(trauma)
##   dose y1 y2 y3 y4 y5
## 1    1 59 25 46 48 32
## 2    2 48 21 44 47 30
## 3    3 44 14 54 64 31
## 4    4 43  4 49 58 41
library(VGAM)
fit <- vglm(cbind(y1,y2,y3,y4,y5) ~ dose, family=cumulative(parallel=TRUE), data=trauma)
summary(fit)
## 
## Call:

The fitted values shown here are the 5 estimated multinomial response probabilities for each of the 4 treatment groups.

Note: propodds() is another possible family for vglm; it defaults to cumulative(reverse = TRUE, link = ”logit”, parallel = TRUE).

We can also model dose-response data without proportional odds, using vglm() in VGAM library without parallel=TRUE option.

fit2 <- vglm(cbind(y1,y2,y3,y4,y5) ~ dose, family=cumulative, data=trauma)
summary(fit2)

The improvement in fit is statistically significant, but perhaps not substantively significant; effect of dose is moderately negative for each cumulative probability.

We can also fit cumulative probit model:

fit.cprobit <- vglm(cbind(y1,y2,y3,y4,y5) ~ dose, family=cumulative(link=probitlink, parallel=TRUE), data=trauma)
